# Dependency Injection (DI): Constructor Injection:

    # A Real-Life Starting Point: Running a Mobile Repair Shop:

            Imagine you’re the owner of a small mobile repair shop. Every time a customer walks in with a problem — say a broken screen
            or a software issue — you start looking for your tools: screwdriver, tester, tweezers, etc.

            This routine becomes tiring, right? So, what do you do? You decide to prepare a toolkit. Now,
            whenever someone brings in a damaged phone, everything you need is already packed and ready.
            You just open your kit and begin. This toolkit is like Constructor Injection.

            Instead of hunting for tools every time (creating objects manually), you prepare everything at the beginning and
            give it to the technician when they start working. This is exactly what Constructor Injection does in programming —
            all necessary items (dependencies) are provided when the object is created.


Q1. Why Constructor Injection Matters?
    In Java, you often write code like this:
        Student student = new Student();

    You manually create the object. If you have multiple dependencies, you may end up writing a lot of repetitive and tightly
    connected code. This becomes difficult to maintain, especially in larger applications. Constructor Injection changes this.

    Spring creates all required objects for you and gives them to your class at the time of creation. You don’t manually call
    new everywhere. This makes your code cleaner, more modular, and easier to manage.

  # Real-Life Analogy:
    Think of a laptop. When you buy a laptop, it already has an operating system (Windows, Linux, etc.) installed.
    You don’t install it every time. This is similar to Constructor Injection.
    Here, the laptop is your service class, and the operating system is the dependency it needs to function.

# Key Points to Remember:
    1. Spring creates objects and injects dependencies using your constructor.
    2. You define everything in the XML using <constructor-arg>.
    3. This method is clean, safe, and highly recommended for required dependencies.
    4. It follows the IoC principle — Spring controls everything.

# Some Common Interview Questions and Answers:

    Q1: What is Constructor Injection in Spring?
     A: Constructor Injection is a type of dependency injection where dependencies are provided to a class through its constructor.
        In Spring, the IoC container creates the object and injects its dependencies by calling the constructor with required arguments,
        which are defined in the XML using <constructor-arg>.

    Q2: Why should we use Constructor Injection instead of Setter Injection?
     A: 1. Constructor Injection is used when all dependencies are mandatory. It ensures that the object is created with all required resources.
           If any dependency is missing, the object will not be created — which helps avoid errors.
        2. Setter Injection, on the other hand, is better for optional dependencies.

    Q3: Can we have both Constructor and Setter Injection in the same class?
     A: Yes, Spring allows a mix of both. However, it’s recommended to use Constructor Injection for required dependencies
        and Setter Injection for optional ones to keep the design clean and maintainable.

    Q4: What happens if multiple constructors are present in a class? How does Spring decide which one to use?
     A: If multiple constructors are present, Spring will try to match the constructor based on the number and type of
        <constructor-arg> elements provided in the XML. If it cannot find a proper match, it will throw a BeanCreationException.

    Q5: Is Constructor Injection supported in annotations-based configuration?
     A: Yes. In annotations-based configuration, you can use @Autowired on a constructor, and Spring will automatically inject
        the dependencies. However, this example used XML configuration as it’s still widely used in Spring 3.x projects.